pr_title: Segregation of Dev and Prod envs
pr_body:
This pull request will start the addition of testing modules for the entire codebase.

The various packages needed for this task are -
- Pytest-Django - This is a modified pytest package useful to test Django projects
- Factory-Boy - This is a factory data generator package that will help us to generate data for tests
- Faker - A package that generates fake data for testing

Structural changes to the repo
- A folder named `tests` would be created in the project's root folder, which will have sub-folders named as the respective Django app names.
- Conftest file in the root will help us to declare all data factories in one place.
- Pytest.ini in root is a generic setting file for pytest and its behaviour.

@mgogoulos please let me know if this proposed method requires any further changes. Once we finalized this process, we can then proceed to start writing tests for every respective django app

Perhaps we should create another one that uses this as the base', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 18, 19, 54, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657360412, 'comment_body': "We should not be changing this docker-compose, it's used for production. ```
.
.
.
.
  web:
    build:
      context: .
      dockerfile: ./Dockerfile.dev
    image: mediacms/mediacms-dev:latest
    ports:
      - "80:80"
    volumes:
      - ./:/home/mediacms.io/mediacms/
    depends_on:
      redis:
        condition: service_healthy
      db:
        condition: service_healthy
  db:
    image: postgres
    volumes:
      - ../postgres_data:/var/lib/postgresql/data/
    restart: always
    environment:
      POSTGRES_USER: mediacms
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: mediacms
      POSTGRES_DB: mediacms
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD-SHELL", "pg_isready -U mediacms"]
      interval: 10s
      timeout: 5s
      retries: 5
  redis:
    image: "redis:alpine"
    restart: always
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD", "redis-cli","ping"]
      interval: 30s
      timeout: 10s
      retries: 3
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 21, 13, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 658289216, 'comment_body': 'This extends requirements.txt, so add `-r requirements.txt` to the top of the file

You need to create a `Dockerfile.dev` that adds these requirements to a dev docker image', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 21, 19, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 658472055, 'comment_body': "Actually we don't need to write all of them again. If we simply run
`docker-compose -f docker-compose.yaml -f docker-compose.dev.yaml up` it will run docker-compose first and then overrite non-existant settings from docker-compose.dev and run them", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 25, 4, 51, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'shubhank-saxena', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 658541942, 'comment_body': 'Good suggestion, I would use `extends` (https://docs.docker.com/compose/extends/#extending-services) instead of depending on the user getting the command line right - though it is not supported in compose versions after 2.1 :(

Also, take note:

* some services have been removed (in dev mode they will all run in the web container)
* the `Dockerfile.dev` is used to create the image for the web container in dev mode', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 25, 7, 40, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 659147936, 'comment_body': 'I think you still need to copy the db and redis service into this file. Using the chained `docker-compose -f file1 -f file2` will merge settings from file1 to file2. So the web service will get Environment variables that have intentionally been removed from here (so defaults are used)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 26, 9, 58, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 659148306, 'comment_body': 'Feels like this should extend the `mediacms/mediacms:latest` and since it is a dev image, it does not need a 2 stage build.

The file below should be sufficient -

```
FROM mediacms/mediacms:latest

SHELL ["/bin/bash", "-c"]

# Set up virtualenv
ENV VIRTUAL_ENV=/home/mediacms.io
ENV PATH="$VIRTUAL_ENV/bin:$PATH"
ENV PIP_NO_CACHE_DIR=1

RUN cd /home/mediacms.io && python3 -m venv $VIRTUAL_ENV

COPY requirements.txt . 
COPY requirements-dev.txt .
RUN pip install -r requirements-dev.txt

WORKDIR /home/mediacms.io/mediacms
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 26, 10, 2, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 659209229, 'comment_body': 'Makes sense!

pr_title: Segregation of Dev and Prod envs
pr_body:
This pull request will start the addition of testing modules for the entire codebase.

The various packages needed for this task are -
- Pytest-Django - This is a modified pytest package useful to test Django projects
- Factory-Boy - This is a factory data generator package that will help us to generate data for tests
- Faker - A package that generates fake data for testing

Structural changes to the repo
- A folder named `tests` would be created in the project's root folder, which will have sub-folders named as the respective Django app names.
- Conftest file in the root will help us to declare all data factories in one place.
- Pytest.ini in root is a generic setting file for pytest and its behaviour.

@mgogoulos please let me know if this proposed method requires any further changes. Once we finalized this process, we can then proceed to start writing tests for every respective django app

[{'comment_id': 657358467, 'comment_body': 'This docker file is optimized for production, we should not be adding test artifacts to it (these will bloat it, yet they are not needed for the runtime).

Perhaps we should create another one that uses this as the base', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 18, 19, 54, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657360412, 'comment_body': "We should not be changing this docker-compose, it's used for production. Create another which uses the image (with test artifacts) mentioned above", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 18, 22, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657361467, 'comment_body': 'Again these are not needed in the production image, we need to separate prod requirements and dev/test requirements', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 18, 24, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 658281174, 'comment_body': 'All these are dev dependencies and should be placed in the requirements-dev.txt', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 21, 4, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 658286209, 'comment_body': 'This is incomplete, below to the list of services:

```
.
.
.
.
  web:
    build:
      context: .
      dockerfile: ./Dockerfile.dev
    image: mediacms/mediacms-dev:latest
    ports:
      - "80:80"
    volumes:
      - ./:/home/mediacms.io/mediacms/
    depends_on:
      redis:
        condition: service_healthy
      db:
        condition: service_healthy
  db:
    image: postgres
    volumes:
      - ../postgres_data:/var/lib/postgresql/data/
    restart: always
    environment:
      POSTGRES_USER: mediacms
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: mediacms
      POSTGRES_DB: mediacms
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD-SHELL", "pg_isready -U mediacms"]
      interval: 10s
      timeout: 5s
      retries: 5
  redis:
    image: "redis:alpine"
    restart: always
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD", "redis-cli","ping"]
      interval: 30s
      timeout: 10s
      retries: 3
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 21, 13, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 658289216, 'comment_body': 'This extends requirements.txt, so add `-r requirements.txt` to the top of the file

You need to create a `Dockerfile.dev` that adds these requirements to a dev docker image', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 21, 19, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 658472055, 'comment_body': "Actually we don't need to write all of them again. If we simply run
`docker-compose -f docker-compose.yaml -f docker-compose.dev.yaml up` it will run docker-compose first and then overrite non-existant settings from docker-compose.dev and run them", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 25, 4, 51, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'shubhank-saxena', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 658541942, 'comment_body': 'Good suggestion, I would use `extends` (https://docs.docker.com/compose/extends/#extending-services) instead of depending on the user getting the command line right - though it is not supported in compose versions after 2.1 :(

Also, take note:

* some services have been removed (in dev mode they will all run in the web container)
* the `Dockerfile.dev` is used to create the image for the web container in dev mode', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 25, 7, 40, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 659147936, 'comment_body': 'I think you still need to copy the db and redis service into this file. Using the chained `docker-compose -f file1 -f file2` will merge settings from file1 to file2. So the web service will get Environment variables that have intentionally been removed from here (so defaults are used)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 26, 9, 58, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 659148306, 'comment_body': 'Feels like this should extend the `mediacms/mediacms:latest` and since it is a dev image, it does not need a 2 stage build.

The file below should be sufficient -

```
FROM mediacms/mediacms:latest

SHELL ["/bin/bash", "-c"]

# Set up virtualenv
ENV VIRTUAL_ENV=/home/mediacms.io
ENV PATH="$VIRTUAL_ENV/bin:$PATH"
ENV PIP_NO_CACHE_DIR=1

RUN cd /home/mediacms.io && python3 -m venv $VIRTUAL_ENV

COPY requirements.txt . 
COPY requirements-dev.txt .
RUN pip install -r requirements-dev.txt

WORKDIR /home/mediacms.io/mediacms
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 26, 10, 2, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'swiftugandan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 659209229, 'comment_body': 'Makes sense!
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 26, 18, 35, 9, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'shubhank-saxena', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 659727951, 'comment_body': "I don't understand this. So when we run chained command, it inherits non changed values.
